  Day5MetBeforeDialog: []
  Day6Dialog:
  - "We set our tents near Marsa, where spring water is barely enough for all. They
    call for surgeons and elders to tend to men struck already in first skirmishes.
    I believed myself ready\u2014years in the corps, steady hands\u2014but the smoke
    and screams here are no book lesson. By tomorrow, I suspect I will realise my
    training was for ease, not for men who may die where they fall."
  Day7FirstTimeDialog:
  - Wounded arrive in numbers far beyond what we foresaw. After heavy attacks, thousands
    lie torn or broken, some left in mud-filled trenches because there are no bearers.
    The field outside our huts is chaos; cries rise with each sunset. By tomorrow,
    I fear I will adopt the grim surrender of forgetting names, counting only the
    bodies I might save.
  Day7MetBeforeDialog:
  - "Yesterday, I still believed I could find a rhythm\u2014a method to subtract
    pain if not death. Today, a young Janissary looked at me with eyes asking if
    he\u2019d see his home again. Words failed; I offered tea and cooling cloths.
    Even as his breathing faltered, I explained nothing, whispering prayers not entirely
    my own. By tomorrow, I suspect such rituals will feel like the only mercy left."
  Day8FirstTimeDialog:
  - "Some beg us to stop, not from pain but from the hopelessness of it all. Our
    tents overflow. Evacuation by galley to Tripoli is too slow\u2014many never leave
    these fields alive. Disease stalks the camp as surely as enemy bullets. By tomorrow,
    I fear I will weigh suffering against the number we cannot help and choose merely
    to stop the worst, a choice I once thought impossible."
  Day8MetBeforeDialog:
  - "Last night, I prayed for no more wounded to arrive so we might catch our breath.
    It was a prayer for myself, not for them. Dawn brought a fresh tide of cries.
    I saw men weeping not just from pain but from sheer exhaustion and despair. By
    tomorrow, I suspect I will no longer pray at all\u2014just grind through each
    breath with stony resolve."
  Day9FirstTimeDialog:
  - "The camp feels cursed; water runs scarce, and the wounds fester. The hospital
    at Marsa was once orderly\u2014now it is full, overflowed into galleys anchored
    in harbour. The cries echo against wood and canvas. By tomorrow, only the hardest
    among us will stand, the rest broken by the sights and smells that know no mercy."
  Day9MetBeforeDialog:
  - "Today, our camp was struck by cavalry from outside. Wounded men, some barely
    able to stand, fled in panic. I saw a soldier once mourning his own brother suddenly
    run, as if life\u2019s terror outweighed death\u2019s certainty. By tomorrow,
    I suspect uniforms and allegiances will blur\u2014only the human gasp of fear
    and the ache of loss will remain."
  Day10FirstTimeDialog:
  - My hands no longer tremble. Once I worried this meant mastery; now it feels like
    numbness. Mud, blood, and dirt have become the palette of every dawn. Men die
    where they lie, some without even a whisper of prayer. By tomorrow, I fear I
    will accept silence as enough.
  Day10MetBeforeDialog:
  - "I no longer reach for texts of wisdom. I reach for water, for clean cloth, for
    any balm. I fear what I will carry back home\u2014not the honour of arms but
    the memory of those left dying in trenches, abandoned in dust-filled earth. If
    there is a tomorrow, will this memory haunt my quiet rooms like a phantom? I
    suspect it will."
